President Trump has signed a directive that aims to refocus America's space program on human exploration and discovery. The directive marks an important step in returning American astronauts to the moon for the first time since 1972, with the goal of establishing a foundation for an eventual mission to Mars. President Trump believes that space exploration has many other applications, including military ones, and wants America to remain the leader in this field. Vice President Pence, who leads the National Space Council, praised the directive as a momentous occasion in the history of American space exploration. He emphasized that returning to the moon is vital to achieving strategic objectives and ensuring national security. Additionally, Pence believes that the directive will spur innovation and create jobs.